As regards ethnological details, which Mela distributes with a lavish and reckless hand, it may be said that there is per- haps no ancient treatise, professedly scientific and didactic, which so teems with grotesque information, culled from the rich storehouse of Hellenic fancy, myth, and anecdote, for everything is grist that comes to his rhetorical mill. Pliny the Elder, omnivorous reader that he was, does, indeed, cite the Chorossraplnu of Mela as among his sources, but there- after all germine traces of its influence disappear until the early Middle Ages.
